<subSubSection pageId="14" pageNumber="15" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="14.[151,1436,151,788]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[201,323,547,572]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" reason="1">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
This new species can be distinguished from its congeners by the forewing having a tuft of erect deep-yellow scales beneath posteriad of fold at 3/5. It resembles 
<taxonomicName authority="Li &amp; Zhang &amp; Sinev, 2012" authorityName="Li &amp; Zhang &amp; Sinev" authorityYear="2012" box="[884,1049,584,608]" class="Insecta" family="Cosmopterigidae" genus="Scaeosopha" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="spinivalvata" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[884,898,584,608]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">S</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[912,1049,584,608]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">spinivalvata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1057,1148,584,608]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1057,1148,584,608]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
in the male genitalia, but can be separated by the finger-shaped valvellae: the left one with narrowly rounded apex and the right one with rounded apex and the long and narrow cornutus (
<figureCitation box="[696,780,655,679]" captionStart="FIGURES 31–34" captionStartId="12.[151,264,1615,1638]" captionTargetBox="[245,1343,213,1582]" captionTargetId="figure-122@12.[226,1360,195,1594]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="FIGURES 31–34. Male genitalia of Scaeosopha spp. 31, S. percnaula Meyrick (= S. stagnigera Meyrick syn. nov., lectotype, genitalia slide no. JFGC7765); 32, S. sinevi Ponomarenko et Park, genitalia slide no. ZZW08211; 33, S. betrokensis sp. nov., holotype, BMNH Microlep. slide no. 32345, 33a, eighth sternum; 34, S. erecta sp. nov., holotype, genitalia slide no. ZZW09004." pageId="14" pageNumber="15">Fig. 34</figureCitation>
); in 
<taxonomicName authority="Li &amp; Zhang &amp; Sinev, 2012" authorityName="Li &amp; Zhang &amp; Sinev" authorityYear="2012" box="[828,992,656,680]" class="Insecta" family="Cosmopterigidae" genus="Scaeosopha" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="spinivalvata" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[828,842,656,680]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">S</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[855,992,656,680]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">spinivalvata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[998,1087,656,680]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[998,1087,656,680]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
, the valvellae are spine-shaped in distal 1/4 and acuminate apically, and the cornutus is shorter and differently shaped (
<figureCitation box="[1127,1212,692,716]" captionStart="FIGURES 39–42" captionStartId="18.[151,263,1943,1966]" captionTargetBox="[232,1344,669,1889]" captionTargetId="figure-286@18.[226,1360,637,1922]" captionTargetPageId="18" captionText="FIGURES 39–42. Male genitalia of Scaeosopha spp. 39, S. spinivalvata sp. nov., holotype, BMNH Microlep. slide no. 31023; 40, S. tuberculata sp. nov., holotype, genitalia slide no. ZZW08050; 41, S. victoriensis sp. nov., holotype, BMNH Microlep. slide no. 32349; 42, S. incantata Meyrick, BMNH Microlep. slide no. 31006." pageId="14" pageNumber="15">Fig. 39</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="14" pageNumber="15" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="14.[151,1436,151,788]" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[201,335,728,752]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" reason="1">Etymology.</emphasis>
The specific epithet is derived from the Latin 
<emphasis box="[853,933,729,752]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="15">erectus</emphasis>
= erect, referring to the tuft of erect scales at 3/5 wing length beneath fold on the forewing.
</paragraph>
